    {
      "step_id": "95e8d717",
      "step_index": 5,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "hERG blockers commonly have:\n1) **A basic center** (protonated) that can engage electrostatic interactions in the pore (often with residues like **Thr/Ser** region and stabilizing interactions near **Phe656/Tyr652** via cation\u2013\u03c0 / \u03c0\u2013\u03c0).\n2) **Hydrophobic/aromatic groups** that occupy lipophilic pockets and form **\u03c0-stacking** with key aromatic residues in the channel.\n3) **Appropriate spacing** (often ~5\u20137 \u00c5 from cationic N to aromatic centroid(s)) and a shape that can adopt a \u201c**Y/T-shaped**\u201d arrangement.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:48:35.794407+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "4b755462",
      "step_index": 6,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "This molecule has:\n- A **protonatable piperidine N** (strong driver for binding).\n- **At least two substantial aromatic systems** (anilide phenyl + fused aromatic heterocycle) providing **\u03c0-surfaces**.\n- A **benzylic CH2 linker** from phenyl to piperidine N \u2192 common spacing motif in many hERG-active chemotypes.\n- Amides add polarity and can reduce passive permeability somewhat, but **do not remove the key cationic + aromatic pharmacophore**. In many cases, adding amides reduces hERG *only if* it disrupts lipophilicity/geometry enough; here the aromatic bulk remains high.",
      "tool_name": null,
